\frac{\cos x}{\cos y}=\frac{a}{b}
a \tan x +b \tan y
(a+b) \cot\frac{x+y}{2}
(a+b)\tan\frac{x+y}{2}
(a+b)(\tan\frac{x}{2} +\tan\frac{y}{2})
(a+b)(\cot\frac{x}{2}+\cot\frac{y}{2})
\frac{\cos x}{\cos y} = \frac{a}{b} 
\frac{\cos x +\cos y}{\cos x -\cos y} = \frac{a+b}{a-b}
\frac{2\cos\frac{x+y}{2}\cos\frac{x-y}{2}}{2\sin\frac{x+y}{2}\sin\frac{y-x}{2}}
\frac{2\cos\frac{x+y}{2}\cos\frac{x-y}{2}}{2\sin\frac{x+y}{2}\sin\frac{y-x}{2}} = -\cot\Bigl(\frac{x+y}{2}\Bigr)\cdot\Bigl(\frac{x-y}{2}\Bigr)=\frac{a+b}{a-b}
\tan(y) =\frac{a+b}{2a} \times \biggl\{\tan\left(\frac{x+y}{2}\right)-\tan\left(\frac{x-y}{2}\right)\biggr\}
\tan(x)
a
\tan(y)
b
\frac a{\cos x}=\frac b{\cos y}=\frac{a+b}{\cos x+\cos y}
\implies a\tan x+b\tan y=\frac a{\cos x}\cdot\sin x+\frac b{\cos y}\cdot\sin y
\displaystyle\frac a{\cos x},\frac b{\cos y}
a\tan x+b\tan y=(\sin x+\sin y)\frac{(a+b)}{\cos x+\cos y}
\displaystyle \cos x+\cos y=2\cos\frac{x+y}2\cos\frac{x-y}2
\displaystyle \sin x+\sin y=2\sin\frac{x+y}2\cos\frac{x-y}2
